article.headline: Charlotte 65, Fairleigh Dickinson 59
article.story: CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- An'Juan Wilderness scored 17 points as Charlotte held off a second-half rally to beat Fairleigh Dickinson 65-59 on Sunday Leemire Goldwire and Ian Andersen added 11 points each for the 49ers (8-4), who led by as many as 14 points midway through the second half. Manny Ubilla scored 18 points, Sean Baptiste added 13 and Eric Hazard 11 for the Knights (4-6), who shot just just 29.7 percent from the field and had their three-game winning streak snapped. After trailing by 10 points at the break, Fairleigh Dickinson opened the second half with a 14-4 run -- capped by a Hazard 3-pointer with 16:17 remaining -- that cut Charlotte's lead to 42-39. But Andersen hit a 3 and a pair of free throws and Charlie Coley's dunk kicked off a 15-4 run that pushed the 49ers' lead back to 57-43 with 7:46 left. The Knights made another run late in the second half, cutting Charlotte's lead down to four points twice, the last at 61-56 with 46.2 seconds left. But Goldwire tied up Ubilla for a key turnover 10 seconds later, and the 49ers hit 4-of-6 from the free throw line over the last 30 seconds to preserve their second straight win. The Knights led twice in the opening minutes of the first half, the last at 7-4 on Hazard's hook shot with 15:44 left. But Wilderness' three-point play 43 seconds later tied the score, and Andersen's 3-pointer with 14:22 remaining put the 49ers ahead. Fairleigh Dickinson managed to stay within five points until the later stages of the first half, when a 7-0 Charlotte run put the 49ers up 29-17 -- their biggest lead of the period -- with 6:29 left. The Knights managed to cut Charlotte's lead back under double digits three times in the final five minutes, the last at 33-25 on a pair of Ubilla free throws with 1:15 left. But Goldwire drove for a layup off a steal with 12.4 seconds remaining to give the 49ers a 35-25 lead at the break.
